        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12.0pt;\">In the clinical evaluation of a patient with a strong family history of colorectal cancer, which of the following characteristics is not consistent with familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP)?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4894558",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32087,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. A) Autosomal recessive inheritance</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>FAP is an autosomal dominant </strong>condition</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Familial polyposis syndrome (FAP) is an <strong>autosomal domi足nant</strong> disorder.</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">It is caused by<strong> mutation in the adeno足matous polyposis coli or APC gene on chromosome 5q21</strong>.</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">A<strong>t least 100 polyps </strong>are necessary for a diagnosis of FAP.</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Since <strong>colorectal carci足noma develop in 100% of untreated FAP </strong>patients often <strong>before age 30</strong>, so,<strong> prophylactic colectomy is the standard therapy </strong>in patients with APC mutations.</span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B.&nbsp;Screening </strong>for polyps in individuals with<strong> FAP or at risk of FAP </strong>is typically performed with <strong>sigmoidoscopy or colonoscopy</strong>, as <strong>polyps </strong>tend to occur throughout the colon.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C.&nbsp;Polyp </strong>development in FAP usually <strong>starts in the teenage years </strong>or <strong>early adulthood </strong>and if<strong> left untreated</strong>, these polyps can lead to <strong>colorectal cancer, </strong>often before the age of 30.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D.&nbsp;Associated features of FAP </strong>may include various extracolonic manifestations, including <strong>epidermal cysts, osteomas, and other benign growths</strong>, which are<strong> true.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP) </strong>is an <strong>autosomal dominant disorder</strong>, not an autosomal recessive condition.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Ref</u>: Robbins 10<sup>th</sup>/ 812</strong></span></p>",
