      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 59113,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Juvenile polyp</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 59114,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Adenomatous polyp</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 59115,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Tubulovillous polyp</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 59116,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Peutz Jegher polyp</span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A 17-year-old presented with intussusception and was found to be having a polyp. A biopsy is taken and is shown alongside. What is the likely diagnosis in this individual?</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2023/05/08/picture1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"288\"></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q1627453",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32084,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. D) Peutz Jegher polyp</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\">The<strong> Peutz-Jegher polyp </strong>is part of an <strong>autosomal dominant syndrome </strong>characterized by <strong>hamartomatous polyps </strong>throughout the <strong>gastrointestinal tract</strong>. The biopsy showing an <strong>arborizing pattern aligns </strong>with the diagnosis of<strong> Peutz-Jeghers syndrome, </strong>fitting with the patient's clinical presentation</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Juvenile polyps</strong> <strong>do not </strong>typically cause <strong>intussusception in older children or teenagers </strong>and are not characterized by an arborizing architecture on histology.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Adenomatous polyps</strong> are <strong>neoplastic </strong>and could be associated with <strong>intussusception; </strong>however, they <strong>do not show </strong>the <strong>arborizing histological pattern </strong>seen in the provided biopsy.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Tubulovillous adenomas</strong> are <strong>not typically associated with the genetic syndrome </strong>in question and <strong>do not </strong>have the <strong>arborizing architecture </strong>shown in the biopsy.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">The <strong>histological pattern of the polyp </strong>and the clinical presentation of<strong> intussusception at a young age </strong>suggest a diagnosis of<strong> Peutz-Jeghers syndrome. </strong>This condition is associated with <strong>hamartomatous polyps </strong>that have a <strong>tree-like architectural pattern </strong>and <strong>increased cancer risk.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Ref</u>: Robbins 10<sup>th</sup> 809-810</strong></span></p>",
      "correct_choice_id": 59116,
