        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">In Peutz-Jeghers syndrome, polyps are mainly seen in:</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8662399",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32086,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. D) Jejunum</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">The <strong>polyps of Peutz-Jeghers syndrome (PJS) </strong>are <strong>most com足mon in the small intestine especially jejunum</strong>, although they may occur in the stomach and colon, and, with much lower frequency, in the bladder and lungs.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">The<strong> jejunum is the most frequently </strong>affected site, and patients with <strong>Peutz-Jeghers syndrome </strong>often develop polyps here that can cause complications like <strong>intussusception.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A.&nbsp;Rectal involvement </strong>is possible in<strong> Peutz-Jeghers syndrome</strong>, but it is <strong>not the primary site of polyp </strong>development.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B.&nbsp;</strong>The <strong>colon can be involved</strong>, but the <strong>small intestine</strong>, particularly the <strong>jejunum, is the most common site for polyps </strong>in this syndrome.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C.</strong>&nbsp;Esophageal polyps are quite<strong> uncommon in Peutz-Jeghers syndrome</strong>, with the condition typically affecting the small intestine.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Jejunum </strong>is the<strong> most common site </strong>for the characteristic<strong> hamartomatous polyps of Peutz-Jeghers syndrome.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Location of Polyps in PJS:</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/image_x5vzrZQ.png\" width=\"1033\" height=\"293\"></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Ref:</u> Robbins 10<sup>th</sup>/ 809</strong></span></p>",
      "correct_choice_id": 59060,
