          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Decreased breakdown of &beta;-catenin</span></span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 54558,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Increased breakdown of &beta;-catenin</span></span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 54559,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Lack of production of &beta;-catenin</span></span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 54560,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Decreased activity of &beta;-catenin</span></span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 42-year-old male undergoes a colectomy. The pathologist identifies more than 100 polyps in the resected specimen as well as a focus of invasive adenocarcinoma. Of the following, what is the functional mechanism of the gene mutation causing his disease process?</span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3498913",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32085,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A) Decreased breakdown of &beta;-catenin</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">This patient suffers from<strong> Familial Adenomatous Polyposis</strong>, one of the <strong>genetic colon cancer syndromes. </strong>In this disorder, patients have a <strong>germline loss of function </strong>mutation in the <strong><em>APC tumor suppressor gene, which usually functions to break down &beta;-catenin</em></strong>, a protein involved in the <strong>signal cascade of APC</strong>.&nbsp; The subsequent <strong>increased amount of &beta;-catenin </strong>appears to <strong>prevent cell differentiation and apoptosis</strong>. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Decreased breakdown of &beta;-catenin&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The<strong> APC gene </strong>is a<strong> tumor suppressor gene </strong>that, when functional, <strong>promotes the breakdown of &beta;-catenin</strong>. A<strong> loss-of-function mutation </strong>in the<strong> APC gene</strong>, as seen in <strong>FAP, </strong>results in<strong> decreased degradation of &beta;-catenin</strong>, leading to its <strong>accumulation in the cell </strong>and subsequent<strong> increase in cell proliferation and decrease in cell death</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B. Increased breakdown of &beta;-catenin:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">An increased breakdown of &beta;-catenin would actually be a<strong> protective mechanism against the development of neoplasia</strong>, as it would<strong> prevent </strong>the <strong>excessive cell proliferation </strong>associated with <strong>colorectal cancer</strong>. This is <strong>not the mechanism involved in FAP</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Lack of production of &beta;-catenin:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<strong>FAP </strong>is <strong>not </strong>characterized by a<strong> lack of production of &beta;-catenin</strong>. Instead,<strong> &beta;-catenin production is normal</strong>, but<strong> its breakdown </strong>is<strong> impaired </strong>due to the <strong>non-functional APC protein.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Decreased activity of &beta;-catenin&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In<strong> FAP</strong>, <strong>&beta;-catenin </strong>activity is <strong>not decreased</strong>. In fact, <strong>due to the loss of APC function and decreased breakdown of &beta;-catenin</strong>, its activity within the<strong> Wnt signaling pathway is increased</strong>, leading to enhanced <strong>transcription of proliferation genes</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong> </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In<strong> Familial Adenomatous Polyposis</strong>, <strong>mutations </strong>in the <strong>APC tumor suppressor gene </strong>lead to <strong>decreased breakdown of &beta;-catenin</strong>, which <strong>accumulates in the nucleus and activates transcription factors </strong>that promote<strong> cell proliferation and reduce apoptosis</strong>, contributing to the<strong> development of colorectal neoplasia</strong>. <strong>APC </strong>is also called as <strong>Gatekeeper of Colonic Neoplasia </strong>and its <strong>locus is on chromosome 5q21.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>",
