      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. A) Rb</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Retinoblastoma gene </strong>is<strong> not </strong>typically associated with<strong> colon carcinoma</strong>. Mutations in <strong>Rb </strong>are more commonly linked to <strong>retinoblastoma and other cancers.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B. Mismatch repair genes</strong>: Mismatch repair genes, such as <strong>MLH1, MSH2, MSH6, and PMS2, are associated with Lynch syndrome </strong>(<strong>hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer </strong>or HNPCC), which<strong> predisposes </strong>individuals to <strong>colorectal cancer</strong>.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C. APC (Adenomatous Polyposis Coli):&nbsp;Mutations in the APC gene </strong>are a well-established <strong>genetic alteration </strong>in <strong>colorectal cancer. </strong>Loss of APC function contributes to the initiation of colorectal adenomas, which can progress to carcinoma.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D. Beta-catenin:&nbsp;</strong>Beta-catenin plays a role in the<strong> Wnt signaling pathway, and mutations in the CTNNB1 gene</strong> (encoding beta-catenin) can lead to abnormal activation of this pathway, contributing to<strong> colorectal cancer development.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:#0d0d0d;font-size:12pt;\">The<strong> correct answer is (a). </strong>The <strong>Rb gene is not commonly associated with colon carcinoma; </strong>it is<strong> more closely associated with</strong> <strong>retinoblastoma</strong> and other types of cancer.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Colon carcinoma can arise through two major molecular pathways:</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/image_K7Ztc8k.png\" width=\"1157\" height=\"303\"></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Ref</u>: Robbins 10<sup>th</sup>/ 815</strong></span></p>",
